Japan, China, India, Thailand, Malaysia: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-04-26T22:18:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-26/japan-china-india-thailand-malaysia-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry will release at
8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its report on Japan’s retail sales in March.
Retail sales dropped 6.1 percent last month from a year earlier
after rising 0.1 percent in February, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey before the
government data.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.215 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
81.58 per dollar at 7:08 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : The government will sell 30 billion yuan ($4.6
billion) of 20-year bonds.  China Development Bank  plans to
auction 15 billion yuan of 10-year bonds and 20 billion yuan of
10-year floating-rate bonds.  The yield on the government’s 3.77 percent bond due
December 2020 was at 3.92 percent, according to Chinabond, the
nation’s biggest debt-clearing house. The yuan was at 6.5287 per
dollar.  India : The government will sell a combined 100 billion
rupees ($2.2 billion) of 91-day and 182-day bills.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.09
percent. The rupee was at 44.49 per dollar.  Malaysia: The government will sell 3.5 billion ringgit
($1.2 billion) of 10-year Islamic bonds.  Bank Negara  will offer
1 billion ringgit of 131-day Islamic notes and a combined 2
billion ringgit of 128- and 210-day debt.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was at 4.09 percent. The ringgit was at 2.988 per dollar.  Singapore : The government will sell S$3.6 billion ($2.9
billion) of 365-day Treasury bills.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.46 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2339.  South Korea: Gross domestic product expanded 4.2 percent in
the three months through March from a year earlier, less than
4.7 percent in the previous quarter, according to the median
estimate in a Bloomberg News survey before official data today.  The yield on  South Korea ’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.83 percent. The won was at 1,086.30 per dollar.  Thailand: The government will sell a combined 24 billion
baht ($800 million) of bonds due 2015 and 2025.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.29 percent. The baht was at 30 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in Singapore at 
